      ["What is an income statement?", "A financial statement showing revenues, expenses, and net income over a period."],
      ["Purpose of an income statement?", "To measure a company's profitability for a specific period."],
      ["Scenario: A company earns $50,000 revenue and incurs $30,000 expenses. Which statement reflects this?", "Income statement."],
      ["What is a balance sheet?", "A financial statement showing assets, liabilities, and owner’s equity at a specific point in time."],
      ["Purpose of a balance sheet?", "To provide a snapshot of a company’s financial position on a given date."],
      ["Scenario: Business wants to show what it owns and owes. Which statement?", "Balance sheet."],
      ["What is a statement of owner’s equity?", "A financial statement showing changes in owner’s equity over a period."],
      ["Purpose of a statement of owner’s equity?", "To report investments, withdrawals, and net income affecting equity."],
      ["Scenario: Owner invests $5,000 and withdraws $1,000. Which statement shows this?", "Statement of owner’s equity."],
      ["What is a cash flow statement?", "A statement showing cash inflows and outflows from operating, investing, and financing activities."],
      ["Purpose of a cash flow statement?", "To assess a company’s liquidity and cash management over a period."],
      ["Scenario: Business reports $10,000 cash received from customers and $6,000 paid for expenses. Which statement?", "Cash flow statement."],
      ["Which statement reports net income?", "Income statement."],
      ["Which statement reports total assets?", "Balance sheet."],
      ["Which statement reports beginning and ending equity?", "Statement of owner’s equity."],
      ["Which statement tracks cash from loans and investments?", "Cash flow statement."],
      ["Scenario: Company borrows $5,000 and buys equipment for $3,000. Which statement records cash impact?", "Cash flow statement."],
      ["Scenario: Business wants to show financial health to investors. Which statements to provide?", "Income statement, balance sheet, and cash flow statement."],
      ["What type of financial statement is prepared first?", "Income statement."],
      ["Why prepare financial statements in sequence?", "Net income from income statement flows into owner’s equity statement, affecting the balance sheet."],
      ["Scenario: Company earns $1,200 net income. Which statement shows impact on equity?", "Statement of owner’s equity."],
      ["Which statement shows operating results over time?", "Income statement."],
      ["Which statement shows company’s resources and claims?", "Balance sheet."],
      ["Scenario: Company purchases inventory for cash. Which statement shows the outflow?", "Cash flow statement."],
      ["Scenario: Owner adds $2,000 capital. Which statements are affected?", "Statement of owner’s equity and balance sheet."],
      ["Which statement shows retained earnings?", "Statement of owner’s equity."],
      ["Which financial statement helps evaluate liquidity?", "Cash flow statement."],
      ["Which statement helps evaluate solvency?", "Balance sheet."],
      ["Scenario: Company reports $800 revenue, $500 expenses. Which statement shows profit?", "Income statement."],
      ["Why is the balance sheet considered a snapshot?", "It shows financial position at a single point in time, not over a period."],
      ["Scenario: Owner withdraws $1,000. Which statements are affected?", "Statement of owner’s equity and balance sheet."],
      ["Which statement shows how cash is generated and used?", "Cash flow statement."],
      ["Scenario: Company sells inventory on account. Which statements are affected?", "Income statement and balance sheet."],
      ["Which statement includes assets, liabilities, and equity?", "Balance sheet."],
      ["Which statement reconciles beginning and ending cash balances?", "Cash flow statement."],
      ["Scenario: Preparing financial statements for a fiscal year. Which sequence is correct?", "Income statement → Statement of owner’s equity → Balance sheet → Cash flow statement."]
