      ["What is an asset?", "A resource owned by a business that has economic value and can provide future benefits."],
      ["Scenario: Company buys a delivery truck. Is it an asset?", "Yes, the truck is a fixed asset providing future benefits."],
      ["What is a liability?", "A financial obligation or debt a business owes to an outside party."],
      ["Scenario: Company owes $1,000 to a supplier. Is this an asset or liability?", "Liability; it represents money owed."],
      ["What is accounts payable?", "Amounts a business owes to suppliers for goods or services received on credit."],
      ["Scenario: Company receives $500 of supplies on credit. What account increases?", "Accounts payable increases by $500."],
      ["What is accounts receivable?", "Amounts owed to a business by customers for goods or services sold on credit."],
      ["Scenario: Company sells $300 of merchandise on credit. Which account increases?", "Accounts receivable increases by $300."],
      ["What is owner’s equity?", "The residual interest in the assets of a business after deducting liabilities."],
      ["Scenario: Owner invests $2,000 cash. Which account increases?", "Owner’s equity increases $2,000."],
      ["What is revenue?", "Income earned from a business’s primary operations, like sales of goods or services."],
      ["Scenario: Company earns $1,500 from consulting. Which account increases?", "Revenue increases $1,500."],
      ["What is an expense?", "Costs incurred to generate revenue, decreasing owner’s equity."],
      ["Scenario: Company pays $200 for utilities. Which account decreases?", "Owner’s equity decreases via an expense account."],
      ["What is a withdrawal?", "Cash or assets taken out of the business by the owner for personal use."],
      ["Scenario: Owner takes $400 cash from the business. Which account is affected?", "Owner’s equity decreases via withdrawals."],
      ["What is a journal?", "A detailed record of all business transactions in chronological order."],
      ["Scenario: Recording a sale on account. Which accounting tool is used first?", "The journal."],
      ["What is a ledger?", "A collection of all accounts showing their balances and activity."],
      ["Scenario: Posting from the journal to the ledger. Purpose?", "To summarize transactions by account."],
      ["What is a trial balance?", "A list of all ledger accounts and their balances to check if debits equal credits."],
      ["Scenario: Debits do not equal credits. Which step?", "Check the trial balance for errors."],
      ["What is a general journal?", "A journal used to record all types of transactions in one place."],
      ["Scenario: Business records rent expense, purchase of equipment, and sales. Which journal?", "General journal."],
      ["What is a purchase account?", "An account used to track the cost of goods bought for resale."],
      ["Scenario: Company buys inventory for $800. Which account records this?", "Purchase account."],
      ["What is a sales account?", "An account recording income from selling goods or services."],
      ["Scenario: Company sells $1,000 of products. Which account increases?", "Sales account."],
      ["What is a cash account?", "An account that records all cash receipts and payments."],
      ["Scenario: Business receives $500 in cash from a customer. Which account?", "Cash account increases $500."],
      ["What is a prepaid expense?", "An asset representing payment made in advance for a future expense."],
      ["Scenario: Company pays $600 for 6 months of insurance. Which account?", "Prepaid insurance (asset) increases $600."],
      ["What is a note payable?", "A written promise to pay a specific amount of money on a future date."],
      ["Scenario: Company signs a $2,000 note for equipment. Which account?", "Notes payable (liability) increases $2,000."],
      ["What is a note receivable?", "A written promise from another party to pay the business a certain amount."],
      ["Scenario: Company receives a promissory note from a customer. Which account?", "Notes receivable (asset) increases."],
      ["What is a fixed asset?", "A long-term tangible asset used in operations, like buildings or equipment."],
      ["Scenario: Business buys a computer for office use. Which type of asset?", "Fixed asset."],
      ["What is a current asset?", "An asset expected to be converted to cash or used within one year."],
      ["Scenario: Company holds $2,000 in inventory. Type of asset?", "Current asset."]
      ,


      ["What is double-entry accounting?", "A system where every transaction affects at least two accounts with equal debits and credits."],
      ["Scenario: Company buys $500 equipment for cash. How is this recorded?", "Debit Equipment $500, Credit Cash $500."],
      ["What is a debit?", "An entry on the left side of an account that increases assets or expenses and decreases liabilities or equity."],
      ["What is a credit?", "An entry on the right side of an account that increases liabilities, equity, or revenue and decreases assets or expenses."],
      ["Scenario: Company receives $1,000 from a customer on account. Which accounts are debited and credited?", "Debit Cash $1,000, Credit Accounts Receivable $1,000."],
      ["Scenario: Business pays $200 for utilities. How to record?", "Debit Utilities Expense $200, Credit Cash $200."],
      ["What is the main purpose of double-entry accounting?", "To ensure the accounting equation (Assets = Liabilities + Equity) remains balanced."],
      ["Scenario: Owner invests $2,000 cash into the business. How is it recorded?", "Debit Cash $2,000, Credit Owner’s Capital $2,000."],
      ["Which accounts normally have debit balances?", "Assets and expenses usually have debit balances."],
      ["Which accounts normally have credit balances?", "Liabilities, owner’s equity, and revenue usually have credit balances."],
      ["Scenario: Company borrows $5,000 from a bank. Record the transaction.", "Debit Cash $5,000, Credit Notes Payable $5,000."],
      ["What happens if debits and credits are not equal?", "The books are out of balance, indicating an error in recording."],
      ["Scenario: Business pays $600 for prepaid insurance. Record the entry.", "Debit Prepaid Insurance $600, Credit Cash $600."],
      ["Why is double-entry accounting considered more accurate than single-entry?", "It tracks both sides of every transaction, reducing errors and providing a complete picture."],
      ["Scenario: Company earns $1,200 revenue on account. Record the entry.", "Debit Accounts Receivable $1,200, Credit Sales Revenue $1,200."],
      ["What type of account is increased with a debit?", "Asset or expense accounts increase with a debit."],
      ["What type of account is increased with a credit?", "Liability, equity, or revenue accounts increase with a credit."],
      ["Scenario: Owner withdraws $500 cash. How is this recorded?", "Debit Owner’s Drawing $500, Credit Cash $500."],
      ["What is the normal balance of an asset account?", "Debit."],
      ["What is the normal balance of a liability account?", "Credit."],
      ["What is the normal balance of an expense account?", "Debit."],
      ["What is the normal balance of a revenue account?", "Credit."],
      ["Scenario: Business purchases inventory on credit for $800. Record the transaction.", "Debit Inventory $800, Credit Accounts Payable $800."],
      ["Scenario: Company pays $300 on account. Record the transaction.", "Debit Accounts Payable $300, Credit Cash $300."],
      ["Why must every transaction have at least one debit and one credit?", "To maintain the accounting equation and ensure accurate financial records."],
      ["Scenario: Business receives $1,000 from a customer in advance. How to record?", "Debit Cash $1,000, Credit Unearned Revenue $1,000."],
      ["Scenario: Business records $400 depreciation. How to record?", "Debit Depreciation Expense $400, Credit Accumulated Depreciation $400."],
      ["Scenario: Owner withdraws merchandise for personal use. How to record?", "Debit Owner’s Drawing $value, Credit Inventory $value."],
      ["What does it mean when a transaction is 'balanced'?", "Total debits equal total credits."],
      ["Scenario: Business pays $100 for office supplies. How to record?", "Debit Office Supplies Expense $100, Credit Cash $100."],
      ["Scenario: Company earns $500 interest revenue. How is it recorded?", "Debit Cash $500, Credit Interest Revenue $500."],
      ["What is the effect of a debit on owner’s equity?", "It decreases owner’s equity through expenses or withdrawals."],
      ["What is the effect of a credit on owner’s equity?", "It increases owner’s equity through capital contributions or revenues."],
      ["Scenario: Company issues $2,000 in common stock for cash. Record the transaction.", "Debit Cash $2,000, Credit Common Stock $2,000."],
      ["Scenario: Business pays $150 for rent. Record the entry.", "Debit Rent Expense $150, Credit Cash $150."],
      ["Scenario: Company collects $700 from a customer on account. Record the transaction.", "Debit Cash $700, Credit Accounts Receivable $700."]
      ,


      ["What is the primary purpose of accounting?", "To record, summarize, and report financial information for decision-making."],
      ["Scenario: A small business wants to track profits. Which role of accounting applies?", "Monitoring profitability through accurate financial records."],
      ["How does accounting support investors?", "Provides financial information to evaluate a company’s performance and make investment decisions."],
      ["Scenario: Investor reviews a company’s income statement. What accounting purpose is served?", "Assessing profitability and potential returns."],
      ["How does accounting help managers?", "By providing data to plan, control, and make strategic business decisions."],
      ["Scenario: Manager analyzes monthly expenses to cut costs. Which accounting role is this?", "Managerial accounting for internal decision-making."],
      ["How does accounting support creditors?", "Supplies financial information to assess the ability of a business to repay debts."],
      ["Scenario: Bank reviews a company’s balance sheet before granting a loan. Purpose of accounting?", "Evaluating creditworthiness and financial stability."],
      ["What role does accounting play in taxation?", "Provides accurate records to calculate and report taxes owed."],
      ["Scenario: Business prepares tax returns. How does accounting help?", "Ensures compliance with tax laws and accurate reporting."],
      ["How does accounting improve transparency in the economy?", "By reporting reliable financial data, it builds trust among stakeholders."],
      ["Scenario: Public company releases audited financial statements. Role of accounting?", "Enhancing transparency and investor confidence."],
      ["What is financial accounting?", "Recording and reporting business transactions for external users like investors and regulators."],
      ["What is managerial accounting?", "Providing financial data to help managers make internal decisions."],
      ["Scenario: Company uses cost reports to set product prices. Which accounting type?", "Managerial accounting."],
      ["How does accounting support economic growth?", "By enabling efficient allocation of resources through informed decisions."],
      ["Scenario: Business identifies profitable products using accounting data. Economic role?", "Optimizing resources and driving growth."],
      ["Why is accuracy important in accounting?", "Inaccurate data can lead to poor decisions, financial loss, and legal issues."],
      ["Scenario: Accountant finds a misposted transaction. Why correct it?", "To maintain accurate records and reliable reports."],
      ["How does accounting affect business planning?", "Provides historical and current data for budgeting and forecasting."],
      ["Scenario: Company creates a yearly budget. Accounting role?", "Supporting planning and financial control."],
      ["What is the social role of accounting?", "Helps ensure businesses are accountable to stakeholders and society."],
      ["Scenario: Company reports environmental fines in financial statements. Accounting purpose?", "Transparency and social accountability."],
      ["How does accounting support risk management?", "By identifying financial risks and providing information to mitigate them."],
      ["Scenario: Company evaluates cash flow risk before expansion. Accounting role?", "Assessing financial risk to guide decisions."],
      ["Why is accounting considered the language of business?", "It communicates financial information clearly to stakeholders for decision-making."],
      ["Scenario: CEO reviews monthly reports to make investment choices. Accounting purpose?", "Communicating financial health for informed decisions."],
      ["How does accounting assist in regulatory compliance?", "By tracking transactions and preparing reports according to laws and standards."],
      ["Scenario: Business submits audited reports to the SEC. Role of accounting?", "Ensuring legal compliance and accurate reporting."],
      ["What role does accounting play in pricing decisions?", "Provides cost and revenue data to set competitive and profitable prices."],
      ["Scenario: Manager calculates product costs before launching a new line. Accounting purpose?", "Cost analysis for pricing strategy."],
      ["How does accounting influence public trust?", "Reliable reporting builds confidence in businesses and markets."],
      ["Scenario: Company issues quarterly financial statements. Trust role of accounting?", "Maintaining credibility with investors and the public."],
      ["How does accounting aid internal controls?", "Tracks transactions and prevents fraud or mismanagement."],
      ["Scenario: Company reconciles bank statements monthly. Accounting role?", "Monitoring internal controls and safeguarding assets."],
      ["Why is accounting important for strategic decisions?", "It provides data-driven insights to guide growth and investment."],
      ["Scenario: Board decides to expand internationally based on financial analysis. Accounting purpose?", "Supporting strategic decision-making."]
