      ["Cost of Sales", "The direct costs of producing goods or services sold by a business, including materials and labor."],
      ["General Operating Expenses", "Expenses incurred in the regular operation of a business that are not directly tied to production, like rent, utilities, and salaries."],
      ["Asset", "A resource owned by a business that provides future economic benefits."],
      ["Expense", "A cost incurred in the process of earning revenue, recorded in the period it is used."],
      ["Supplies Inventory", "Supplies purchased but not yet used, recorded as an asset on the balance sheet."],
      ["Supplies Expense", "The cost of supplies used during a period, recorded on the income statement."],
      ["Transaction Recording as Asset", "Recording a purchase as an asset when it provides future benefit."],
      ["Transaction Recording as Expense", "Recording a purchase as an expense when it benefits only the current period."],
      ["Sales Dollars", "The total revenue generated from selling products or services."],
      ["Sales Units", "The number of items sold or expected to be sold to achieve a target revenue."],
      ["Net Income", "The profit remaining after all expenses and taxes are deducted from revenue."],
      ["Contribution Margin", "The amount remaining from sales revenue after variable expenses have been deducted, used to cover fixed costs and profit."],
      ["Contribution Margin Rate", "Contribution margin expressed as a percentage of sales."],
      ["Breakeven Point (Units)", "The number of units that must be sold to cover all fixed and variable costs, resulting in zero profit."],
      ["Breakeven Point (Sales Dollars)", "The amount of sales revenue needed to cover all costs, resulting in zero profit."],
      ["Planned Net Income", "The target profit a business aims to achieve for a specific period."],
      ["Calculate Sales for Target Net Income", "Using fixed costs, variable costs, and desired net income to determine required sales dollars or units."],
      ["Variable Costs", "Costs that change directly with the level of production or sales, such as materials and direct labor."],
      ["Fixed Costs", "Costs that remain constant regardless of production or sales volume, such as rent or salaries."],
      ["Direct Labor", "The wages paid to workers directly involved in producing goods or services."],
      ["Direct Materials", "Raw materials that become part of the finished product."],
      ["Indirect Costs", "Costs that are not directly tied to production, often considered part of operating expenses."],
      ["Gross Profit", "Sales revenue minus cost of sales."],
      ["Operating Income", "Gross profit minus operating expenses."],
      ["Inventory Turnover", "A ratio showing how many times inventory is sold and replaced over a period."],
      ["Markup", "The amount added to the cost of a product to determine its selling price."],
      ["Margin", "The difference between sales revenue and cost of sales, expressed as a percentage of sales."],
      ["Target Sales Units Example", "If net income target is $10,000, fixed costs $50,000, and contribution margin per unit is $20, then units needed = (50,000 + 10,000)/20 = 3,000 units."],
      ["Target Sales Dollars Example", "If desired net income is $5,000, fixed costs $30,000, and contribution margin ratio is 40%, sales dollars needed = (30,000 + 5,000)/0.4 = $87,500."],
      ["Supplies Used Example", "Purchased $500 in office supplies, used $300; $300 recorded as Supplies Expense, $200 remains in Supplies Inventory."],
      ["Cost of Sales Example", "Selling 100 units at $50 each, cost per unit $30, total cost of sales = 100*30 = $3,000."],
      ["Operating Expenses Example", "Monthly rent $1,500, utilities $200, and salaries $3,000 are recorded as operating expenses."],
      ["Asset vs Expense Timing Example", "Buying a $1,000 laptop for office use is an asset; buying $50 in printer paper is an expense."],
      ["Contribution Margin Per Unit Example", "Selling price $25, variable cost $15, contribution margin = $10 per unit."],
      ["Contribution Margin Ratio Example", "Sales $100, variable costs $60, contribution margin ratio = (100-60)/100 = 40%."],
      ["Breakeven Units Example", "Fixed costs $20,000, contribution margin $50/unit, breakeven units = 20,000/50 = 400 units."],
      ["Breakeven Sales Dollars Example", "Fixed costs $15,000, contribution margin ratio 30%, breakeven sales = 15,000/0.3 = $50,000."],
      ["Net Income Goal Units Example", "Fixed costs $10,000, contribution margin $25/unit, target net income $5,000, required units = (10,000+5,000)/25 = 600 units."],
      ["Net Income Goal Dollars Example", "Fixed costs $12,000, contribution margin ratio 25%, target net income $3,000, required sales = (12,000+3,000)/0.25 = $60,000."],
      ["Inventory Expense Timing Example", "Supplies purchased in January, used in February, recorded as expense in February."],
      ["Direct vs Indirect Cost Example", "Wood used in making chairs is direct cost; factory electricity is indirect cost."],
      ["Variable vs Fixed Cost Example", "Commission paid per sale is variable; office lease is fixed."],
      ["Revenue Recognition Example", "Revenue recorded when goods are delivered or services performed."],
      ["Operating vs Non-Operating Income Example", "Revenue from core business is operating; gain from selling old equipment is non-operating."],
      ["Profit Margin Example", "If sales $50,000 and net income $5,000, profit margin = 10%."],
      ["Expense Allocation Example", "Depreciation allocated monthly from asset purchase."],
      ["Cost Flow Example", "FIFO, LIFO, or weighted average methods affect cost of sales calculation."],
      ["Target Sales Planning Example", "Adjusting price or volume to reach desired net income."],
      ["Cash vs Accrual Example", "Cash basis records revenue when received; accrual basis when earned."],
      ["Real-Life Scenario: Retail", "Retail store tracks inventory as assets; supplies used in store operations recorded as expenses."],
      ["Real-Life Scenario: Manufacturing", "Raw materials and direct labor recorded as cost of sales; factory rent recorded as operating expense."],
      ["Real-Life Scenario: Service Business", "Office supplies are expensed; service fees earned recorded as revenue."],
      ["Example: Seasonal Inventory", "Company buys winter coats in October; inventory recorded as asset until sold in December."],
      ["Example: Variable vs Fixed Mix", "A bakery has flour (variable) and oven lease (fixed), used to calculate breakeven."],
      ["Example: Contribution Margin Strategy", "Reducing variable costs increases contribution margin and lowers breakeven point."],
      ["Example: Net Income Planning", "Company sets net income target and calculates required sales units and dollars."],
      ["Example: Supplies Usage", "Printing paper bought at start of year expensed as used monthly."],
      ["Example: Operating Expenses Control", "Monitoring utilities and salaries to maintain operating expenses within budget."]
